    "summarizer": {
      "general_reader_takeaway": "This paper tests a modified gravity model \u2014 called \"Hybrid f(Q)\" \u2014 as a geometric alternative to the cosmological constant, fitting it against data on how the universe expands and how large-scale structures grow. The review board found the perturbation-sector analysis potentially interesting but identified a significant internal contradiction: the paper claims the model is observationally indistinguishable from standard cosmology in background data, yet the paper's own results show background data actually prefer the Hybrid model. Until this inconsistency is resolved and the statistical formulas are independently verified, the main conclusions cannot be relied upon.",
      "reviewer": "claude",
      "technical_takeaway": "The paper derives that the linear f(Q) coupling \u03b1 must equal 1 to avoid catastrophic Early Dark Energy domination at high redshift, then asserts this forces complete \u039bCDM background degeneracy. All three reviewers independently identified that Section V.1 simultaneously reports background-only AIC/DIC improvements and reconstructed q\u2080/w_eff\u2080 values that differ from \u039bCDM, which directly contradicts the degeneracy claim. Two reviewers flagged that the DIC formula in Eq. (23) computes 2p_D (the effective parameter penalty) rather than the standard DIC = 2D\u0304 \u2212 D_min, calling all DIC-based model comparisons into question. The G_eff suppression result is borrowed from a prior reference under the quasi-static approximation without re-derivation or stability verification for this specific model, and the \"amplitude compensation mechanism\" is a standard MCMC parameter degeneracy present in any modified gravity model where G_eff < G."
    }
